04243nam a22005055i 9780887553042DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20022002xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808875530427 a10.1515/97808875530422doi  a(DE-B1597)664676  a(OCoLC)1412009530  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxcCA 7aHIS0060102bisacsh04a614.421 aHackett, Paul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Very Remarkable Sickness :bEpidemics in the Petit Nord, 1670 to 1846 /cPaul Hackett. 1aWinnipeg, Manitoba : bUniversity of Manitoba Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (316 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aManitoba Studies in Native History ;v1400tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of Diagrams, Tables, Maps, and Illustrations -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tOld World Disease Transmission Patterns -- tThe Early Historical Period in the Petit Nord: 1670-1837 -- tThe Smallpox Epidemic of 1737-1738 -- tEpidemic Disease in the Petit Nord: 1739-1780 -- tThe Smallpox Epidemic of 1779-1783 -- tEpidemic Disease in the Petit Nord: 1784-1818 -- tThe Measles and Whooping Cough Epidemics of 1819-1820 -- tEpidemic Disease in the Petit Nord, 1821-1845 -- tThe Epidemics of 1846 -- tConclusion -- tEndnotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe area between the Great Lakes and Lake Winnipeg, bounded on the north by the Hudson Bay lowlands, is sometimes known as the "Petit Nord." Providing a link between the cities of eastern Canada and the western interior, the Petit Nord was a critical communication and transportation hub for the North American fur trade for over 200 years.Although new diseases had first arrived in the New World in the 16th century, by the end of the 17th century shorter transoceanic travel time meant that a far greater number of diseases survived the journey from Europe and were still able to infect new communities. These acute, directly transmitted infectious diseases – including smallpox, influenza, and measles – would be responsible for a monumental loss of life and would forever transform North American Aboriginal communities.Historical geographer Paul Hackett meticulously traces the diffusion of these diseases from Europe through central Canada to the West. Significant trading gatherings at Sault Ste. Marie, the trade carried throughout the Petit Nord by Hudson Bay Company ships, and the travel nexus at the Red River Settlement, all provided prime breeding ground for the introduction, incubation and transmission of acute disease. Hackettís analysis of evidence in fur-trade journals and oral history, combined with his study of the diffusion behaviour and characteristics of specific diseases, yields a comprehensive picture of where, when, and how the staggering impact of these epidemics was felt.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / Pre-Confederation (to 1867).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755304240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887553042423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887553042/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles